@node part4 "How to use the program"

            Enter a balance to begin with, (the currency is unimportant but
            do not enter a currency sign such as Ł,$, etc.).

            Enter a rate of interest which can be between 0.01 and 100,
            (again do not enter a percentage sign).

            Finally, enter the number of years you want to calculate over.
            The maximum number allowed is 99.

            Next, the program gives you the option to receive intermediate
            balance reports. The cycle gadget is by default set to 'No',
            so if you want them you will have to change it to 'Yes'.

            The radio buttons below that allow you to specify the frequency
            of the reports in years. Note that if a report should appear in
            the final year it will not be generated as there is little point
            in doing so. The intermediate reports will appear in requesters.

            When you finally push the 'OK' button, the calculation will be
            done and the results displayed at the bottom of the window.

            To clear all the data in the window and start again, hit the
            'Clear' button.


                                    @{"Return to contents" link main}
@endnode

@node part5 "Bugs"

            Unfortunately, the program is not yet perfect, so there are some
            bugs you need to be aware of.

            The entry gadgets are limited in the size of number they can accept
            but it is still possible to enter large numbers which could crash
            the program when performing the calculations.

            Helpfully however, the program can be run as many times as you want,
            even although a previous copy has crashed.

            The intermediate reports do not always appear if the number of years
            is a very low number.

            The program is not finished and many more features will be added.


                                    @{"Return to contents" link main}
@endnode

@node part6 "Why did I create it?"

    I recently opened a new long-term bank account and was trying to establish,
    given the account's interest rate, how much money I would have in 15 years.

    I found this a difficult and time-consuming task on a calculator and also
    found it quite difficult to have to perform 15 seperate calculations.

    As I'm sure other people have these problems, I decided to try writing a
    program to do the work for me. Creating the formula was easy, it took a
    bit longer to get the GUI together.

    This program is one of a series of programs I have set myself and has kept
    me occupied while working on something much bigger which may appear in the
    next year or so.


                        @{"Return to contents" link main}
@endnode

